{
  "texts": [
    "Privacy Preservation in FedLLMDeep learning models, particularly those of substantial size, have the capacity to memorize training data, which could raise privacy concerns [118,119,120].",
    "The risk is accentuated in LLMs, which due to their expansive capacity, can inadvertently memorize and potentially expose even more detailed information [121].",
    "This situation poses a dual challenge: ensuring the model's effectiveness without compromising individual privacy.To address these concerns, one classical solution is the implementation of differential privacy techniques, which add controlled noise to the model gradients or updates [122], providing a theoretical privacy guarantee for FL.",
    "Another potential solution is to limit the amount of training data of each client [123] or include non-private data [124] such that the private data is less frequently exposed to the LLM, which requires a trade-off between under-fitting and reducing memorization.",
    "Efficiency in FedLLMEfficiency is one fundamental topic in FL [21], including training efficiency since clients need to afford the training process, and communication efficiency since FL requires multi-round communication between server and clients."
  ]
}